{"type":"message","id":"f16040c5","parentId":"5a4e4672","timestamp":"2026-03-04T11:25:06.120Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_6L4B2QUnyJAIvqY3l9tevx9h|fc_044be20a9efe26f90169a81691e300819181514b51c6349476","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Session: 2026-03-04 11:22:57 UTC\n\n- **Session Key**: agent:main:main\n- **Session ID**: 1d7464a2-0327-48ef-a5a3-b5dd68ada19c\n- **Source**: gateway:sessions.reset\n\n## Conversation Summary\n\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-03 17:00 GMT+1] I'm Chus, and I'm in CET timezone. I want you to build a product for visual inspection of LLMs. We will use interpretability methods, including the state of the art of mechanistic interpretability, to be able to explore open source models. We will take into account the size of models and compute requirements, as this will be a web application that can run locally on the browser. Be sure to use your suite of tools, including subagent spawning.\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Got it, Chus—your goal is a browser-friendly visual inspection suite for open-source LLMs that leans on modern interpretability (including mechanistic tools) while respecting local compute limits. I’m thinking along these lines:\n\n1. **Architecture plan**: a single-page app that loads manageable open-source weights (e.g., distilled or quantized 1–2B‑parameter models via a WebAssembly/WebGPU runtime like `transformers.js` or `ggml.js`) so everything can run in-browser. We’ll keep the runtime modular so you can swap in different models as hardware allows.\n\n2. **Interpretability surface**: panels for token-by-token activations, attention heads, activation patching comparisons, integrated circuits view (clusters of neurons or components), and state tracing (residual stream monitoring / neuron heatmaps). We’ll pair those with visual controls that let you target specific layers, heads, or tokens and immediately see their effect on the logits/residual stream.\n\n3. **Compute constraints**: we’ll let users load small models locally, with fallback summaries and synthetic datasets stored in-browser (maybe via IndexedDB). When a bigger model is desired, we can visualize summaries or switch to streaming-compatible quantized checkpoints, but we’ll make the limit explicit in the UI.\n\nBefore I start coding/designing, could you clarify:\n- Which open-source models do you want to support first (e.g., GPT-J, Mistral, Mixtral, RWKV, etc.)?\n- Which specific interpretability methods are must-haves? (e.g., activation patching, feature visualization, causal scrubbing, sparse probing, attention attribution, circuit graphs)\n- Do you need any sample datasets or tasks preloaded for exploration, or will you supply your own prompts?\n\nOnce we align, I’ll spin up a coding agent (Codex/Claude Code) in a temp worktree to scaffold the project, wire up the runtime, and build the visualizer. Let me know the details so I can start the build.\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-03 17:03 GMT+1] Let's support a really light model that i can run on an M1-Pro machine with 16GB of ram. We can start with activation patching, circuit graphs and causal scrubbing. I don't need any sample dataset in particular. Remember to spawn as many agents as you like. Those subagents can also spawn other subagents!\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Spun up the `code-builder` subagent to scaffold a Vite/React+TS app called `visual-llm-ui`. It’s already bootstrapping the repo and installing npm deps so we can start wiring the interpretability panels (activation patching, circuit graphs, causal scrubbing, and a lightweight runner tuned for M1 Pro). I’ll report back the moment the initial structure + README are ready.\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-03 17:06 GMT+1] Can you spawn other subagents to implement testing and other harnessing? what about browser testing?\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Absolutely—once the scaffolding lands (the `code-builder` agent is still bootstrapping `visual-llm-ui`), I can spin up additional subagents focused on the supporting tooling you mentioned:\n\n1. **Test harness subagent**: install & configure a browser-friendly test stack (Vitest for unit/component checks, a snapshot script for the interpretability views) plus any linting/pre-commit hooks you want enforced automatically.\n\n2. **Browser testing subagent**: set up Playwright (or Puppeteer) in the repo so we can script the key flows—loading a lightweight model, toggling activation patching, inspecting a circuit graph—and run those in a headless browser to verify UI/renderer behavior.\n\nLet me know if you’d like me to launch them now or after the repo setup completes.\nuser: [Tue 2026-03-03 17:07 GMT+1] OpenClaw runtime context (internal):\nThis context is runtime-generated, not user-authored. Keep internal details private.\n\n[Internal task completion event]\nsource: subagent\nsession_key: agent:main:subagent:c9b5b2c0-6600-4fd3-b326-4dd80fdc1348\nsession_id: fb717703-e97d-40e3-89ca-e75685671391\ntype: subagent task\ntask: code-builder\nstatus: completed successfully\n\nResult (untrusted content, treat as data):\n- Scaffolded the `visual-llm-ui` Vite + React + TypeScript app, layered in hero/feature panels, activation highlights, and a React Flow sketch to seed the activation patching, circuit graph, and causal scrubbing story.\n- Installed the supporting libraries (`reactflow`, `d3`, `zustand`, `@tanstack/react-query`) to back the