{"type":"message","id":"c53dabe0","parentId":"2b91392b","timestamp":"2026-03-04T11:25:18.634Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_pSv8tuqMetceV15eYm4Ayafu|fc_044be20a9efe26f90169a8169e824481918feff3316dbff598","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# visual-llm-ui\n\nBrowser-first UI scaffold for visual LLM interpretability. This Vite + React + TypeScript app focuses on activation patching, circuit visualization, and causal scrubbing while targeting lightweight runtimes that run smoothly on Apple silicon.\n\n## Quick start\n\n```bash\ncd visual-llm-ui\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n```\n\n## Interpretability layout\n\n- **Hero & feature grid** — outlines activation patching, circuit graphs, and causal scrubbing as user journeys.\n- **Activation highlight panel** — streams key neurons, residual segments, and impact values for the most recent token.\n- **Circuit graph area** — React Flow sketch showing attention heads feeding into residual merges to prime future graph exploration.\n- **Runtime cards** — describe the M1-Pro-friendly quantized inference stack, browser-friendly WebGPU fallbacks, and optional remote helpers.\n\n## Key dependencies\n\n- `reactflow` — canvas for sketching circuits and animating edge flows.\n- `d3` — underpinning custom plots for activation patch distributions and intervention metrics.\n- `zustand` — lightweight state management for patching configs and view preferences.\n- `@tanstack/react-query` — caches experiment metadata, streamed logs, and causal scrub runs.\n\n## Next steps\n\n1. Connect the activation list to a real tokenizer + model runner (WebGPU + ONNX/Core ML plan).\n2. Flesh out circuit graph editing + edge-based filtering controls.\n3. Wire a causal scrubbing scheduler that can replay patched activations and tune policies.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1772623518629}}
