- Tests and builds already pass (`npm run build`, `npm run test:unit`, `npm run test:e2e`), so the baseline UI is stable.\n\n### Roadmap for the browser-local interpretability product\n\n**1. Runtime & model hookup**\n- Pick a *reasonably light, open-source model* tuned for M1 Pro / 16 GB RAM (e.g., `llama-2-7b` distilled to 4-bit, `mistral-7b-instruct-q4`, or the tiny-2B `ggml` variants). Quantized checkpoints keep memory + compute under control.\n- Bundle a browser-friendly runtime (`ggml.js`, `transformers.js`, or a WebGPU/WebAssembly runner) that can load the quantized weights entirely in the browser. Provide fallbacks:\n  - Local WebGPU/WebNN execution for inference/activations.\n  - Optional remote proxy for heavier checkpoints (only when the user explicitly asks).\n- Build a `ModelRunner` module that exposes tokenization, residual stream hooks, and layer outputs via `zustand` state so the UI can react to new activations instantly.\n\n**2. Activation patching workflow**\n- Replace the placeholder activation data with real residual/neuronal stats streamed from the `ModelRunner`.\n- Implement a `PatchLayer` panel where users can:\n  - Select layer/head/neuron groups.\n  - Save “reference activation snapshots” for later re-injection.\n  - Compare logit deltas when patching the current activations with saved ones.\n- Wire those controls into the “activation highlights” table/matrix so the impact percentages reflect true causal edits.\n\n**3. Circuit graph + mechanistic view**\n- Expand the React Flow canvas into an interactive “circuit map”:\n  - Nodes represent attention heads, MLPs, residual merges, and logit heads.\n  - Edges can be weighted/colored based on attribution / activation magnitude for the current token.\n  - Allow filtering (e.g., show only heads whose activations change >x% after patching).\n- Add a sidebar to drill into any node (show neuron IDs, positional signals, gating behavior) and hook it into the same instrumentation used for activation patching.\n\n**4. Causal scrubbing studio**\n- Create a scheduler that reruns the current prompt with target interventions:\n  - “Scrub” by zeroing-out selected activations, “replace” with traced values, or mix between runs.\n  - Capture logit trajectories (e.g., distance to a reference token, probability shift for biased terms).\n- Visualize the scrub results with small charts (e.g., D3 line charts for logit changes, heatmap for probability shifts).\n- Surface a timeline/panel that lets users replay the prompt, toggle patches, and see the effect on logits + circuit edges live.\n\n**5. UX & compute transparency**\n- Expand the runtime cards into tappable “runtime switches” (M1 Pro, WebGPU, remote) that show:\n  - Estimated VRAM/CPU usage (based on model size + token length).\n  - Expected latency + throughput.\n- Keep a “compute budget” indicator that warns if the model + prompt combo might exceed the available resources and offers quantized alternatives (e.g., switch from 4B to 2B or shorten the prompt).\n\n### Next steps (implementation plan)\n1. **Design runtime API** – build `src/runtime` with tokenization + WebGPU runner + `zustand` store for activations.\n2. **Hook UI components** – update `ActivationsMatrix`, `PromptControl`, and new panels (patching controls, scrubbing timeline, circuit node inspector) to consume runtime data.\n3. **Add instrumentation** – capture activation snapshots, log patches, and compute causal metrics (delta logits, path contributions) in the store so charts can consume them.\n4. **Polish e2e flows** – keep Playwright/Vitest coverage in sync as we add interactivity (mocked data for tests to avoid heavy inference runs).\n\nSince you asked to keep everything local and avoid subagents, I’ll run these edits interactively in this session. Want me to start with wiring the runtime + activations store, or do you prefer to flesh out the UI/visualization spec first?","textSignature":"msg_044be20a9efe26f90169a816b8a87c81918e3d1a2f9d791fc9"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.1-codex-mini","usage":{"input":479,"output":2475,"cacheRead":18176,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21130,"cost":{"input":0.00011975,"output":0.0049499999999999995,"cacheRead":0.00045440000000000004,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.005524149999999999}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772623532263}}
